body_text.text: (XLS 99 KB) Additional file 3: Summary GWAS finding for ASD Meta-analysis ("European" Ancestries); Data reported on P < 10E-4.
All numerical data are available at Dataset S1.
Microarray-based methylome data are available at Array-Express (E-MTAB-5797).
All the genomic data used for analyses are freely available to be downloaded from the GEO repository (GSE55306).
The RNA-seq data generated in this study have been deposited in DDBJ under accession codes DRA001101 and DRA004790 (Supplementary Table
RNA sequencing data have been deposited in the Gene Expression Omnibus (GEO) under the accession number GSE100242.
MATLAB code for the surrogate data procedure is available at https://github.com/neurophysics/spurious_
The code of the pipeline and the fully processed data sets are made available to the public via The Virtual Brain website (thevirtualbrain.org)
WES and RNA-Seq data have been deposited at the European Genomephenome Archive (accession number EGAS00001001847).
See also FigureS6and Data S5 and S6.
Code used for the 16S rDNA data analysis has been uploaded to a github repository (https:// github.com/almlab/analysis-salt-responsive).
Raw files of the bacterial V4-V5 16S rRNA data and the L. murinus genome have been uploaded to the NCBI Sequence Read Archive as Bioproject PRJNA400793.

Two Chemokine structures have already been published and are included in our pool of templates (CCR5; PDB ID: 4MBS and CXCR4; PDB ID: 4ODU), therefore template selection and homology modeling of CCR2 should be relatively straightforward.
The output for complex disease comparison is also included (Supplementary Dataset 3).
Realistic Concentration Jumps (RCJ) scripts are available at https://github.com/aplested/aligator.
